  "readingTitle": "What is the difference between an equation and an identity?",
  "reading": "<p>Both use an equals-type sign, but they mean different things.</p>\n            <ul>\n              <li>An <strong>equation</strong> is true only for particular value(s) of the variable. \\( 2x + 1 = 7 \\) is true <em>only</em> when \\( x = 3 \\); you <em>solve</em> it.</li>\n              <li>An <strong>identity</strong> is true for <em>every</em> value of the variable. We use the sign \\( \\equiv \\) to signal this: \\[ (x + 1)^2 \\equiv x^2 + 2x + 1. \\] Whatever number you put in for \\( x \\), both sides are equal.</li>\n            </ul>\n            <p>Index laws (later cards) are identities: \\( a^m \\times a^n \\equiv a^{m+n} \\) holds for all valid \\( a, m, n \\). You will meet \\( \\equiv \\) when a question asks you to prove or \"show that\" two expressions are the same.</p>",
