  "source": "learn",
  "type": "mcq",
  "marks": 1,
  "readingTitle": "What are the three main index laws?",
  "reading": "<p>An <strong>index</strong> (or <strong>power</strong>) tells you how many times to multiply the <strong>base</strong> by itself: \\( a^4 = a \\times a \\times a \\times a \\). Three laws let you combine powers of the <em>same base</em>.</p>\n            <table class=\"worked\">\n              <tr><td><strong>Multiplying</strong> — <em>add</em> the indices: \\[ a^m \\times a^n = a^{m+n}. \\] e.g. \\( 2^3 \\times 2^4 = 2^{7} = 128 \\).</td></tr>\n              <tr><td><strong>Dividing</strong> — <em>subtract</em> the indices: \\[ a^m \\div a^n = a^{m-n}. \\] e.g. \\( x^7 \\div x^2 = x^{5} \\).</td></tr>\n              <tr><td><strong>Power of a power</strong> — <em>multiply</em> the indices: \\[ (a^m)^n = a^{mn}. \\] e.g. \\( (y^3)^4 = y^{12} \\).</td></tr>\n            </table>\n            <p><strong>Careful:</strong> the laws only work for the <em>same base</em>. \\( 2^3 \\times 5^2 \\) does <strong>not</strong> simplify by adding indices. When a coefficient is involved, deal with it separately: \\( (2x^3)^2 = 2^2 \\times x^{3 \\times 2} = 4x^6 \\).</p>",
