  "readingTitle": "Misconception check",
  "reading": "<p><strong>❌ Common misconception:</strong> Solving \\( (x+3)^2 = 20 \\) gives \\( x + 3 = \\sqrt{20} \\) only</p><p><strong>✅ The correct idea:</strong> Taking a square root gives \\( \\pm \\). A weak answer keeps one root; a strong answer writes \\( x + 3 = \\pm 2\\sqrt{5} \\), so \\( x = -3 \\pm 2\\sqrt{5} \\) — two roots.</p>",
